{"parse":{"title":"Ribbon farm","pageid":27812799,"revid":831939558,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Ribbon farms</b> (also known as <b>strip farms</b>, <b>long-lot farms</b>, or just <b>long lots</b>)<sup id=\"cite_ref-illinois_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-illinois-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-texas_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-texas-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> are long, narrow land divisions, usually lined up along a waterway.  In some instances, they line a road.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Description\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Description</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#History\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Advantages\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Advantages</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Disadvantage\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Disadvantage</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Description\">Description</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ribbon_farm&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Description\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<table class=\"plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-globalize\" role=\"presentation\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><img alt=\"Globe icon.\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Ambox_globe_content.svg/48px-Ambox_globe_content.svg.png\" width=\"48\" height=\"40\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Ambox_globe_content.svg/73px-Ambox_globe_content.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/Ambox_globe_content.svg/97px-Ambox_globe_content.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"350\" data-file-height=\"290\" /></div></td><td class=\"mbox-text\"><div class=\"mbox-text-span\">The examples and perspective in this section <b>deal primarily with the United States and do not represent a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Countering_systemic_bias\" title=\"Wikipedia:WikiProject Countering systemic bias\">worldwide view</a> of the subject</b>.<span class=\"hide-when-compact\"> You may <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Ribbon_farm&amp;action=edit\">improve this article</a>, discuss the issue on the <a href=\"/wiki/Talk:Ribbon_farm\" title=\"Talk:Ribbon farm\">talk page</a>, or <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Article_wizard\" title=\"Wikipedia:Article wizard\">create a new article</a>, as appropriate.</span>  <small><i>(March 2018)</i></small><small class=\"hide-when-compact\"><i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal\" title=\"Help:Maintenance template removal\">Learn how and when to remove this template message</a>)</i></small></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:352px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Detroit1796.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Detroit1796.jpg/350px-Detroit1796.jpg\" width=\"350\" height=\"238\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Detroit1796.jpg/525px-Detroit1796.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Detroit1796.jpg/700px-Detroit1796.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"4344\" data-file-height=\"2958\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Detroit1796.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Ribbon farms along the <a href=\"/wiki/Detroit_River\" title=\"Detroit River\">Detroit River</a> in 1796, where modern <a href=\"/wiki/Detroit\" title=\"Detroit\">Detroit</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Windsor,_Ontario\" title=\"Windsor, Ontario\">Windsor, Ontario</a> now stand. <a href=\"/wiki/Fort_Detroit\" title=\"Fort Detroit\">Fort Detroit</a> is on the north side of the river at center left, and <a href=\"/wiki/Belle_Isle_Park\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Belle Isle Park\">Belle Isle</a> is to the right.</div></div></div>\n<p>The size of ribbon farms can vary from lot to lot and from place to place.  In <a href=\"/wiki/Illinois\" title=\"Illinois\">Illinois</a>, these lots could be <span class=\"frac nowrap\"><sup>1</sup>&#8260;<sub>4</sub></span> mile (400&#160;m) or more long and only 30\u201340 feet (9\u201312&#160;m) wide.<sup id=\"cite_ref-illinois_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-illinois-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  Near <a href=\"/wiki/Detroit\" title=\"Detroit\">Detroit</a>, the ribbon farms were about 250 feet (75&#160;m) wide and up to 3 miles (5&#160;km) long.<sup id=\"cite_ref-mich_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mich-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>  In <a href=\"/wiki/Texas\" title=\"Texas\">Texas</a>,  lots could be as small as 10 acres (4&#160;ha) in area, or as large as 5 by 20 miles (8 by 32&#160;km).<sup id=\"cite_ref-texas_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-texas-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Farmers of ribbon farms typically, although not universally, built houses on the farm along the river such that the houses on a series of ribbon farms were located near each other.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ribbon_farm&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Ribbon or strip farms were prevalent in diverse areas of the world along rivers; locations where these farms appear include in parts of <a href=\"/wiki/Ireland\" title=\"Ireland\">Ireland</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-irish_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-irish-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Central Europe (particularly in <a href=\"/wiki/Germany\" title=\"Germany\">Germany</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Poland\" title=\"Poland\">Poland</a>), West Africa, <a href=\"/wiki/Hokkaido\" title=\"Hokkaido\">Hokkaido</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Brazil\" title=\"Brazil\">Brazil</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Chile\" title=\"Chile\">Chile</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-texas_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-texas-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  In the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States\" title=\"United States\">United States</a>, ribbon farms are found in various places settled by the French, particularly along the <a href=\"/wiki/Saint_Lawrence_River\" title=\"Saint Lawrence River\">Saint Lawrence River</a>, the Great Lakes,<sup id=\"cite_ref-illinois_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-illinois-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Detroit_River\" title=\"Detroit River\">Detroit River</a> and tributaries,<sup id=\"cite_ref-cod_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-cod-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> and parts of Louisiana.<sup id=\"cite_ref-illinois_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-illinois-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  Some sections of the American Southwest, particularly <a href=\"/wiki/Texas\" title=\"Texas\">Texas</a>, also had ribbon farms laid out.<sup id=\"cite_ref-texas_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-texas-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>It is likely that platting farms in ribbon lots arose independently in various parts of the world.  However, the ribbon farms scattered through the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States\" title=\"United States\">United States</a> probably derive from the European model.<sup id=\"cite_ref-texas_2-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-texas-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  The origin of the ribbon farm in Europe is unclear, but the first recorded appearance of these types of farms was in Germany in the ninth to eleventh century.<sup id=\"cite_ref-texas_2-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-texas-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  These early German long lots were cut through forests or marshes, rather than along rivers, allowing for clustering of houses along a central road.<sup id=\"cite_ref-texas_2-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-texas-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>  From Germany, the pattern spread, notably to western <a href=\"/wiki/France\" title=\"France\">France</a>, where forest, marsh, and river long lots were well-established by the time the French began colonizing the Americas.  By the 1630s, the long-lot pattern had been imported to the New World<sup id=\"cite_ref-illinois_1-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-illinois-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> and established along the <a href=\"/wiki/St_Lawrence_Seaway\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"St Lawrence Seaway\">St Lawrence Seaway</a> as the French <a href=\"/wiki/Seigneurial_system_of_New_France\" title=\"Seigneurial system of New France\">seigneurial system</a>.  From there, the ribbon farm plan situated along rivers was carried to other parts of the French colonies, and diffused into some parts of the Spanish colonies.<sup id=\"cite_ref-texas_2-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-texas-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Advantages\">Advantages</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ribbon_farm&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Advantages\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In areas where rivers provided the main form of transportation, the ribbon farm layout gave multiple landowners access to the waterway.<sup id=\"cite_ref-illinois_1-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-illinois-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-seign_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-seign-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>  In addition, the long lots increased variation in soil and drainage within one lot,<sup id=\"cite_ref-seign_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-seign-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> and facilitated plowing by minimizing the number of times oxen teams needed to be turned.<sup id=\"cite_ref-illinois_1-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-illinois-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  Where farmers lived on their lots (rather than in a central village), the ribbon farm fostered communication and socialization, with houses clustered at the ends of the lots.<sup id=\"cite_ref-illinois_1-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-illinois-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-seign_6-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-seign-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>  The ribbon farm also strikes an economic balance, where houses are relatively close together and can be easily and economically accessed, yet the farmers need not spend excessive travel time to reach their fields some distance from a central village.<sup id=\"cite_ref-econ_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-econ-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>  Finally, in those places in the New World where ribbon farms were platted, the division of land into long rectangles was relatively easy to survey and establish boundaries.<sup id=\"cite_ref-seign_6-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-seign-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Disadvantage\">Disadvantage</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ribbon_farm&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Disadvantage\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>One disadvantage was that the agricultural land of a single farmer was awkwardly spread out, often over two or more linear miles, necessitating a long travel time to reach rear parts of the lot.<sup id=\"cite_ref-seign_6-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-seign-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>  However, this disadvantage was generally no more than would have been experienced by peasant farmers living in a central village and walking to their fields.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (July 2010)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ribbon_farm&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Open_field_system\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Open field system\">Open field system</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Seigneurial_system_of_New_France\" title=\"Seigneurial system of New France\">Seigneurial system of New France</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Strip_farming\" title=\"Strip farming\">Strip farming</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Strip_farming_in_Norway\" title=\"Strip farming in Norway\">Strip farming in Norway</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Ribbon_farm&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-illinois-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-illinois_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-illinois_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-illinois_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-illinois_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-illinois_1-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-illinois_1-5\"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-illinois_1-6\"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-illinois_1-7\"><sup><i><b>h</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite id=\"CITEREFJames_Edward_Davis2000\" class=\"citation\">James Edward Davis (2000), <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=NviA8i5MSdcC&amp;pg=PA43#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f=false\"><i>Frontier Illinois: History of the Trans-Appalachian Frontier</i></a>, Indiana University Press, pp.&#160;43\u201344, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-253-21406-8\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-253-21406-8\">0-253-21406-8</a></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Frontier+Illinois%3A+History+of+the+Trans-Appalachian+Frontier&amp;rft.pages=43-44&amp;rft.pub=Indiana+University+Press&amp;rft.date=2000&amp;rft.isbn=0-253-21406-8&amp;rft.au=James+Edward+Davis&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DNviA8i5MSdcC%26pg%3DPA43%23v%3Donepage%26q%26f%3Dfalse&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARibbon+farm\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-texas-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-texas_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-texas_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-texas_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-texas_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-texas_2-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-texas_2-5\"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-texas_2-6\"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-texas_2-7\"><sup><i><b>h</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Terry G. Jordan (March 1974). \"Antecedents of the Long-Lot in Texas\". <i>Annals of the Association of American Geographers</i>. <b>64</b>: 70\u201386. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1111/j.1467-8306.1974.tb00955.x\">10.1111/j.1467-8306.1974.tb00955.x</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Annals+of+the+Association+of+American+Geographers&amp;rft.atitle=Antecedents+of+the+Long-Lot+in+Texas&amp;rft.volume=64&amp;rft.pages=70-86&amp;rft.date=1974-03&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1111%2Fj.1467-8306.1974.tb00955.x&amp;rft.au=Terry+G.+Jordan&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARibbon+farm\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-mich-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-mich_3-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite id=\"CITEREFDavid_Lee_Poremba2006\" class=\"citation\">David Lee Poremba (2006), <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=vL-alUYZF4QC&amp;pg=PA30#v=onepage&amp;q&amp;f